<h2 class="wp-block-heading faq-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<div class="schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block"><div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1623393125914"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Which push-ups work the shoulders?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">All push-up varieties we’ve discussed provide targeted intensity to the shoulders for an effective upper-body workout. The pike push-up, handstand push-up, spider push-up, and T push-up are valuable options that provide varied stimuli.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1727421774858"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Why are shoulder push-ups so hard?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Shoulder push-ups are challenging as they require increased effort from the shoulder muscles to lift the upper body. Instead of relying primarily on the chest, these variations elicit greater effort from the shoulders, which can feel more challenging.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1727421784970"><strong class="schema-faq-question">How many push-ups should I do to grow my shoulders?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">The number of push-ups to perform depends on your training goal and experience level. A recommended baseline for targeting strength building is 3–5 sets of 4–6 reps. Increase the reps as you gain strength and control.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1727421793992"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Can I do shoulder push-ups every day?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">You shouldn’t perform the same type of workout every day, as this can lead to burnout and overuse injuries. You should allow enough time (48–72 hours) between sessions for <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8072992/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">muscle recovery and rebuild</a>. This will optimize gains and results.</p> </div> </div>
